# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: edward-w-berry
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:edward-w-berry/adolph-knopf] Knopf was a member of the National Academy of Sciences and the American Academy of Arts and Sciences.
[src:edward-w-berry/adolph-knopf] He served as president of the Geological Society of America in 1944 and received its Penrose Medal in 1959.
[src:edward-w-berry/adolph-knopf] His second wife, Eleanora Knopf, was a notable geologist and frequent collaborator.
[src:edward-w-berry/adolph-knopf] Knopf was born December 2, 1882, in San Francisco, California, to German American immigrants.
[src:edward-w-berry/adolph-knopf] He grew up with his family on a ranch near Woodside, California.
[src:edward-w-berry/adolph-knopf] Knopf entered the University of California, Berkeley, where he became a student of petrology under Andrew Lawson.
[src:edward-w-berry/adolph-knopf] He earned a Bachelor of Science degree in mining geology in 1904 and a Master of Science degree in 1905.
[src:edward-w-berry/adolph-knopf] That same year he spent the first of six summers surveying the mineral deposits of Alaska for the United States Geological Survey (USGS).
[src:edward-w-berry/adolph-knopf] In 1906 he moved to Washington, D.C., to work for the USGS full-time.
[src:edward-w-berry/adolph-knopf] The Alaskan Division, of which Knopf was one of about a dozen members, was considered the best geologic group in the USGS at that time.
[src:edward-w-berry/adolph-knopf] Knopf's work on tin deposits in the Seward Peninsula became the basis of the dissertation for his Ph.D., which he received from Berkeley in 1909.
[src:edward-w-berry/adolph-knopf] In Alaska he also discovered the minerals hulsite and paigeite.
[src:edward-w-berry/adolph-knopf] In 1911 Knopf was promoted from assistant geologist to geologist.
[src:edward-w-berry/adolph-knopf] Over the next nine years he undertook a series of field projects for the USGS, beginning with the mining district in Montana that includes the Boulder Batholith and continuing to other western states including Nevada and California.
[src:edward-w-berry/adolph-knopf] In the latter state he surveyed the Gold Country.
[src:edward-w-berry/adolph-knopf] After discovering that universities on the eastern seaboard were paying about double the USGS salaries, Knopf left the USGS for a teaching position, and a number of his colleagues followed suit.
[src:edward-w-berry/adolph-knopf] Knopf began at Yale University in January 1920.
[src:edward-w-berry/adolph-knopf] He encouraged students to work with the USGS as he had done; this helped mitigate the agency's brain drain following the departures.
[src:edward-w-berry/adolph-knopf] Knopf began at Yale as an associate professor but was promoted to full professor in 1923.
[src:edward-w-berry/adolph-knopf] He was named the Silliman Professor of Geology in 1937 and a Sterling Professor in 1938.
[src:edward-w-berry/adolph-knopf] He was director of graduate studies from 1933 until his retirement from Yale in 1951.
[src:edward-w-berry/adolph-knopf] Upon retiring he returned to his native Woodside, California, settling not far from his family's old ranch.
[src:edward-w-berry/adolph-knopf] There he accepted a visiting appointment at the Stanford University School of Earth Sciences, where he remained until his death in 1966.
[src:edward-w-berry/adolph-knopf] Knopf's field work continued through his Yale and Stanford appointments, again with a focus on western states.
[src:edward-w-berry/adolph-knopf] He continued his work in the Boulder Batholith and investigated intrusive igneous rock bodies in the Spanish Peaks in Colorado.
[src:edward-w-berry/adolph-knopf] He also contributed to the emerging field of geochronology, putting lower bounds of 2 billion years and later 4.5 billion years on the age of the Earth.
[src:edward-w-berry/adolph-knopf] Knopf was elected to the National Academy of Sciences in 1931.
[src:edward-w-berry/adolph-knopf] He was also a Fellow of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences and of the Geological Society of America.
[src:edward-w-berry/adolph-knopf] He was president of the Geological Society of America in 1944, and he received the Penrose Medal in 1959.
[src:edward-w-berry/adolph-knopf] In 1937 he was vice president of the Society of Economic Geologists.
[src:edward-w-berry/adolph-knopf] In 1908 Knopf married Agnes Burchard Dillon.
[src:edward-w-berry/adolph-knopf] They had three daughters and one son, though one of the daughters died in infancy.
[src:edward-w-berry/adolph-knopf] Agnes died in 1918 in that year's flu pandemic.
[src:edward-w-berry/adolph-knopf] In June 1920, Knopf married fellow USGS geologist Eleanora Frances Bliss, who as Eleanora Knopf became a frequent collaborator and travel companion.
[src:edward-w-berry/adolph-knopf] When Adolph moved to Yale, which did not then hire women, Eleanora worked out of Adolph's office, teaching private classes and still accepting USGS assignments.
[src:edward-w-berry/adolph-knopf] When they moved to California, Stanford hired her as a research associate.
[src:edward-w-berry/adolph-knopf] Knopf died November 23, 1966, in Palo Alto, California.
[src:edward-w-berry/adolph-knopf] In his will he endowed a chaired professorship at Yale.
[src:edward-w-berry/adolph-knopf] The sitting Adolph Knopf Professor of Petrology is Shun-ichiro Karato.
[src:edward-w-berry/adolph-knopf] Adolph and Eleanora Knopf also endowed a graduate fellowship in petrology at Stanford.
[src:edward-w-berry/adolph-knopf] Mount Adolph Knopf in Juneau Borough, Alaska is named after him.
[src:edward-w-berry/albert-w-bally] Bally started his career at Shell Oil Company, retiring as Chief Geologist after 27 years in 1981.
[src:edward-w-berry/albert-w-bally] After retirement, he joined Rice University as chair of the Department of Geology and Geophysics.
[src:edward-w-berry/albert-w-bally] He remained active in the department until his death in 2019.
[src:edward-w-berry/albert-w-bally] In 1988, Bally was elected President of the Geological Society of America.
[src:edward-w-berry/alexander-winchell] Winchell graduated from the Wesleyan University of Middletown, Connecticut, in 1847.
[src:edward-w-berry/alexander-winchell] He then taught at Pennington Male Seminary of New Jersey, Amenia Seminary of New York (where he had previously been a student), an academy in Newbern, Alabama, and the Mesopotamia Female Seminary of Eutaw, the last of which was founded by him.
[src:edward-w-berry/alexander-winchell] He became president of the Masonic University at Selma, Alabama, in 1853.
[src:edward-w-berry/alexander-winchell] He was elected as a member of the American Philosophical Society in 1865.
[src:edward-w-berry/alexander-winchell] In 1854 Winchell entered the service of the University of Michigan as professor of physics and civil engineering.
[src:edward-w-berry/alexander-winchell] Eventually he became professor of geology and paleontology at Michigan.
[src:edward-w-berry/alexander-winchell] In 1859, Winchell was appointed as State Geologist of Michigan for the newly formed second geological survey of the state.
[src:edward-w-berry/alexander-winchell] He held the post until 1863 when the state did not appropriate funding to continue the survey.
[src:edward-w-berry/alexander-winchell] The survey was resumed in 1869, and Winchell was reappointed in April.
[src:edward-w-berry/alexander-winchell] Owing to conflicting opinions between Winchell and his superiors, he resigned in 1871.
[src:edward-w-berry/alexander-winchell] In 1863 Winchell took up a lease on a cotton plantation near Vicksburg, Mississippi, under a plan devised by Gen.
[src:edward-w-berry/alexander-winchell] Lorenzo Thomas to lease plantations along the Mississippi River to loyal men from the North, who would hire black laborers on terms prescribed by the army.
[src:edward-w-berry/alexander-winchell] Winchell organized the Ann Arbor Cotton Company and sold stock to the university's president, whereupon he received a leave of absence to engage in cotton planting.
[src:edward-w-berry/alexander-winchell] General Thomas set wages at a low level ($7 per month for men, $5 for women, minus the cost of medical attention and clothing).
[src:edward-w-berry/alexander-winchell] Even then, many lessees defrauded the freedmen of their earnings.
[src:edward-w-berry/alexander-winchell] In the winter of 1863–64, the Treasury Department briefly assumed control of the Mississippi Valley labor system, mandated a substantial increase in black wages, and contemplated leasing the plantations directly to the freedmen.
[src:edward-w-berry/alexander-winchell] The venture brought him only problems, and after he returned to Michigan in 1864, his brother Martin, who was managing the plantation, was killed by guerrillas.
[src:edward-w-berry/alexander-winchell] In 1872, he was appointed chancellor of Syracuse University.
[src:edward-w-berry/alexander-winchell] The depression of 1873 affected both his personal finances and those of Syracuse, and these troubles led him to resign this position in 1874.
[src:edward-w-berry/alexander-winchell] In 1875, he worked as a professor of geology and zoology at Vanderbilt University.
[src:edward-w-berry/alexander-winchell] There, his views on evolution, as expressed in his book *Adamites and Preadamites: or, A Popular Discussion* (1878), were not acceptable to the University administration because they diverged from Biblical teaching.
[src:edward-w-berry/alexander-winchell] Today the views on the "inferiority of the Negro" (quote from his 1878 book) would probably have been the focus of controversy.
[src:edward-w-berry/alexander-winchell] In any case, he was obligated to resign in 1878.
[src:edward-w-berry/alexander-winchell] In 1888, he co-founded the Geological Society of America in Ithaca, New York along with John J.
[src:edward-w-berry/alexander-winchell] He served as the 3rd president of GSA in 1891.
[src:edward-w-berry/alexander-winchell] He then returned to the University of Michigan, where he was professor of geology and paleontology.
[src:edward-w-berry/alexander-winchell] His work in geology was not so significant as his teaching and popular lectures and writing in this field.
[src:edward-w-berry/alexander-winchell] He was much concerned with reconciling science and religion.
[src:edward-w-berry/alexander-winchell] He was an advocate of theistic evolution.
[src:edward-w-berry/alexander-winchell] The fish **Clear chub** *Hybopsis winchelli* (Girard, 1856) is named after him.
[src:edward-w-berry/alexander-winchell] The University of Michigan named a wing of the West Quad dormitory after Winchell, and Ann Arbor honored him with Winchell Park, a neighborhood park on the city's east side.
[src:edward-w-berry/alexander-winchell] Winchell's name was removed from the dormitory in 2018, and the park was renamed after former Ann Arbor Public Schools board president Harold J.
[src:edward-w-berry/alexander-winchell] In removing Winchell's name, the university described his *Preadamites* as an "unambiguously racist" work.
[src:edward-w-berry/alfred-church-lane] Lane was educated at Harvard University and received his A.B. degree in 1883.
[src:edward-w-berry/alfred-church-lane] Between 1883 and 1885 he taught mathematics at Harvard, then studied at the University of Heidelberg until 1887 before returning to Harvard to earn his Ph.D. in 1888.
[src:edward-w-berry/alfred-church-lane] The following year he joined the Michigan State Geologic Survey as a petrographer, and he remained in that post into 1892 while also serving as an instructor at the Michigan College of Mines.
[src:edward-w-berry/alfred-church-lane] He became assistant state geologist for Michigan in 1892, and from 1899 to 1909 he was the state geologist.
[src:edward-w-berry/alfred-church-lane] Finally, he joined Tufts College in 1892, becoming the Pearson professor of geology and mineralogy.
[src:edward-w-berry/alfred-church-lane] He retired from the college in 1936 as professor emeritus.
[src:edward-w-berry/alfred-church-lane] While at Tufts, he served as vice president of the AAAS Division of Geology in 1907.
[src:edward-w-berry/alfred-church-lane] He received an honorary D.Sc. from Tufts in 1913.
[src:edward-w-berry/alfred-church-lane] From 1922 and 1946 he was chairman for the Committee on the Measurement of Geologic Time for the National Research Council.
[src:edward-w-berry/alfred-church-lane] He served as a member of the Board of Visitors at Harvard Observatory in 1924.
[src:edward-w-berry/alfred-church-lane] Alfred Lane was appointed as consultant of science to the Library of Congress in 1929; the first person to hold that post.
[src:edward-w-berry/alfred-church-lane] In 1931, he was president of the Geological Society of America.
[src:edward-w-berry/alfred-church-lane] He was awarded the Ballou Medal by Tufts College in 1940 for "distinguished service to education and the nation".
[src:edward-w-berry/alfred-church-lane] During his career, he authored 1,087 publications.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The **American Academy of Arts and Sciences** (**The Academy**) is one of the oldest learned societies in the United States.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] It was founded in 1780 during the American Revolution by John Adams, John Hancock, James Bowdoin, Andrew Oliver, and other Founding Fathers of the United States.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] It is headquartered in Cambridge, Massachusetts.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Membership in the academy is achieved through a nominating petition, review, and election process.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The academy's quarterly journal, *Dædalus*, is published by the MIT Press on behalf of the academy, and has been open-access since January 2021.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The academy also conducts multidisciplinary public policy research.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Patton has served as President of the Academy since January 2025.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The first class of new members, chosen by the Academy in 1781, included Benjamin Franklin and George Washington as well as several international honorary members.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The initial volume of Academy *Memoirs* appeared in 1785, and the *Proceedings* followed in 1846.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In the 1950s, the Academy launched its journal *Daedalus*, reflecting its commitment to a broader intellectual and socially-oriented program.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Since the second half of the twentieth century, independent research has become a central focus of the Academy.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In the late 1950s, arms control emerged as one of its signature concerns.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The Academy also served as the catalyst in establishing the National Humanities Center in North Carolina.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In the late 1990s, the Academy developed a new strategic plan, focusing on four major areas: science, technology, and global security; social policy and education; humanities and culture; and education.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In 2002, the Academy established a visiting scholars program in association with Harvard University.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] More than 75 academic institutions from across the country have become Affiliates of the Academy to support this program and other Academy initiatives.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The Academy has sponsored a number of awards and prizes, throughout its history and has offered opportunities for fellowships and visiting scholars at the Academy.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] In July 2013, *The Boston Globe* exposed then president Leslie Berlowitz for falsifying her credentials, faking a doctorate, and consistently mistreating her staff.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] It is modeled on the Science and Engineering Indicators, published biennially by the National Science Board as required by Congress.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Ever since the founding of the Academy, its members have been nominated and elected by peers.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Members of the Academy included not only scientists and scholars, but also writers and artists as well as representatives from the full range of professions and public life.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Throughout the Academy's history, more than 10,000 fellows have been elected.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Astronomer Maria Mitchell was the first woman elected to the Academy, in 1848.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The current membership encompasses over 5,700 members based across the United States and around the world.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Academy members include more than 250 Nobel laureates and more than 60 Pulitzer Prize winners.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] Of the Academy's 14,343 members since 1780, 1,406 are or have been affiliated with Harvard University, 611 with the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, 433 with Yale University, 425 with the University of California, Berkeley, and 404 with Stanford University.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] The following table includes those institutions affiliated with 300 or more members.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] † Excludes members affiliated exclusively with associated national laboratories.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-academy-of-arts-and-sciences] As of 2023, membership is divided into five classes and thirty specialties.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-philosophical-society] The **American Philosophical Society** (**APS**) is an American scholarly organization and learned society founded in 1743 in Philadelphia that promotes knowledge in the humanities and natural sciences through research, professional meetings, publications, library resources, and community outreach.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-philosophical-society] It was founded by the polymath Benjamin Franklin and is considered the first learned society founded in what became the United States.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-philosophical-society] Philosophical Hall, the society's headquarters and a museum, is located just east of Independence Hall in Independence National Historical Park.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-philosophical-society] In 1965, in recognition of the building's history, it was designated a National Historic Landmark.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-philosophical-society] The society has about 1,000 elected members.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-philosophical-society] As of April 2020, 5,710 members had been inducted since its creation.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-philosophical-society] Through research grants, published journals, the American Philosophical Society Museum, an extensive library, and regular meetings, the society supports a variety of disciplines in the humanities and the sciences.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-philosophical-society] The American Philosophical Society was founded as the **Philosophical Society** in 1743 by Benjamin Franklin, James Alexander, Francis Hopkinson, John Bartram, Philip Syng Jr., and others as an offshoot of an earlier club, the Junto.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-philosophical-society] It was common at the time for intellectual societies to invite members from around the world, where the society recruited members from other countries, including Alexander von Humboldt, the Marquis de Lafayette, Baron von Steuben, Tadeusz Kościuszko, and Princess Dashkova.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-philosophical-society] The society lapsed into inactivity by 1746, but was revived in 1767.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-philosophical-society] On January 2, 1769, the society united with the American Society for Promoting Useful Knowledge under the name **American Philosophical Society Held at Philadelphia for Promoting Useful Knowledge**.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-philosophical-society] Franklin was elected the first president.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-philosophical-society] During this time, the society maintained a standing Committee on American Improvements; one of its investigations was to study the prospects for a canal to connect the Chesapeake Bay and the Delaware River.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-philosophical-society] The Chesapeake and Delaware Canal, which had been proposed by Thomas Gilpin, Sr., was built in the 1820s.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-philosophical-society] Following the American Revolutionary War, the society looked for leadership to Francis Hopkinson, one of the signatories of the United States Declaration of Independence.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-philosophical-society] Under his influence, the society received land from the government of Pennsylvania, along with a plot of land in Philadelphia, where Philosophical Hall now stands.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-philosophical-society] Charles Darwin, Robert Frost, Louis Pasteur, Elizabeth Cabot Agassiz, John James Audubon, Linus Pauling, Margaret Mead, Woodrow Wilson, Maria Mitchell, and Thomas Edison were all prominent members of the society.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-philosophical-society] Many members of the Society of the Cincinnati were among the APS's first board members and contributors; the APS and SOC still maintain an informal, collegial relationship.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-philosophical-society] Membership of the APS "honors extraordinary accomplishments in all fields." It has about 1,000 elected members, comprising about 840 "resident" members (United States citizens or those working or living in the United States) and about 160 "international" members.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-philosophical-society] As of February 2025 it had elected 5,890 members since its foundation.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-philosophical-society] Over that history, 220 members have been from Harvard University, 117 from Princeton University, 91 from Stanford University, and 86 from the University of California, Berkeley.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-philosophical-society] In 1786, the society established the Magellanic Premium, a prize for achievement in "navigation, astronomy, or natural philosophy," the oldest scientific prize awarded by an American institution, which it still awards.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-philosophical-society] The society has published the *Transactions of the American Philosophical Society* since 1771.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-philosophical-society] The *Proceedings* have appeared since 1838; they publish the papers delivered at the society's biannual meetings.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-philosophical-society] The society has also published *The Papers of Benjamin Franklin*, Joseph Henry, William Penn, and Meriwether Lewis, and William Clark.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-philosophical-society] Jane Aitken bound 400 volumes for the society.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-philosophical-society] The society also has an expansive archive on framer of the U.S. constitution John Dickinson.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-philosophical-society] APS holds the ACLS Collection (American Council of Learned Societies Committee on Native American Languages, American Philosophical Society) which is a collection of indigenous language documents from around the United States including recordings of the Odawa language from northern Michigan.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-philosophical-society] APS has created a guide to help provide broad coverage of the Native American and Indigenous archival collections at the Library & Museum of the American Philosophical Society.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-philosophical-society] These materials date from 1553 to 2020 and include manuscript, audio, and visual materials relating to Indigenous peoples throughout the Americas.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-philosophical-society] The society also has a collection of manuscripts on the history of the British colonies, Revolutionary War, the history of American science, quantum physics, Charles Darwin and evolution, genetics and the history of technology.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-philosophical-society] Philosophical Hall, at 104 South Fifth Street, Philadelphia, between Chestnut and Walnut Streets, immediately south of Old City Hall, was built in 1785–1789 to house the society and designed by Samuel Vaughan in the Federal style.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-philosophical-society] A third floor was added in 1890 to accommodate the expanding library, but was removed in 1948–1950, when the building was restored to its original appearance for the creation of Independence National Historical Park.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-philosophical-society] In 2001, it was opened to the public as The American Philosophical Society Museum, hosting revolving, thematic exhibitions that explore intersections of history, art, and science.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-philosophical-society] The museum features works of art, scientific instruments, original manuscripts, rare books, natural history specimens, and curiosities of all kinds from the APS's own collections, along with objects on loan from other institutions.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-philosophical-society] In 1789–90, the Library Company of Philadelphia (LCP)—now located at 1314 Locust Street, Philadelphia—built its headquarters, Library Hall, directly across 5th Street from APS.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-philosophical-society] In 1884, LCP sold its building, which was demolished for the expansion of the Drexel & Company Building in 1887.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-philosophical-society] The bank building was itself demolished in the 1950s, during the creation of Independence National Historical Park.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-philosophical-society] In 1958, APS built a new library building on the site, that recreated the façade of LCP's Library Hall.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-philosophical-society] APS restored the former Farmers' & Mechanics' Bank building at 425–29 Chestnut Street, which was built in 1854–55 to the design of John M.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-philosophical-society] Gries in the Italianate style, to serve as a lecture hall.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-philosophical-society] It is the site of meetings and most major events the society hosts.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-philosophical-society] Richardson Hall at 431 Chestnut Street, immediately west of Benjamin Franklin Hall, is the former Pennsylvania Company for Insurances on Lives and Granting Annuities Building, which was built between 1871 and 1873 and designed by Addison Hutton.
[src:edward-w-berry/american-philosophical-society] It contains offices and the Consortium for History of Science, Technology and Medicine.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The **Andes** (/ˈændiːz/ *AN-deez*), **Andes Mountains** or **Andean Mountain Range** (Spanish: *Cordillera de los Andes*; Quechua: *Anti*) are the longest continental mountain range in the world, forming a continuous highland along the western edge of South America.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The range is 8,900 kilometres (5,500 mi) long and 200 to 700 kilometres (120 to 430 mi) wide (widest between 18°S and 20°S latitude) and has an average height of about 4,000 metres (13,000 ft).
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The Andes extend from south to north through seven South American countries: Argentina, Chile, Bolivia, Peru, Ecuador, Colombia, and Venezuela.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Along their length, the Andes are split into several ranges, separated by intermediate depressions.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The Andes are the location of several high plateaus—some of which host major cities such as Arequipa, Bogotá, Cali, Medellín, El Alto, La Paz, Mérida, Santiago and Sucre.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The Altiplano Plateau is the world's second highest after the Tibetan Plateau.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] These ranges are in turn grouped into three major divisions based on climate: the Tropical Andes, the Dry Andes, and the Wet Andes.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The Andes are the highest mountain range outside of Asia.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The range's highest peak, Argentina's Aconcagua, rises to an elevation of about 6,961 metres (22,838 ft) above sea level.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The peak of Chimborazo in the Ecuadorian Andes is farther from the Earth's center than any other location on the Earth's surface, due to the equatorial bulge resulting from the Earth's rotation.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The world's highest volcanoes are in the Andes, including Ojos del Salado on the Chile–Argentina border, which rises to 6,893 metres (22,615 ft).
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The Andes are also part of the American Cordillera, a chain of mountain ranges (cordillera) that consists of an almost continuous sequence of mountain ranges that form the western "backbone" of the Americas and Antarctica.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The etymology of the word *Andes* has been debated.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The majority consensus is that it derives from the Quechua word *anti* "east" as in *Antisuyu* (Quechua for "east region"), one of the four regions of the Inca Empire.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Others suggest that it is in fact from the word *anta* (meaning *copper*) of the older Aymara language.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The term *cordillera* comes from the Spanish word *cordel* "rope" and is used as a descriptive name for several contiguous sections of the Andes, as well as the entire Andean range, and the combined mountain chain along the western part of the North and South American continents.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The Andes mountain range, the longest continental mountain system in the world, extends approximately 7,000 km (4,300 mi) along the western edge of South America, spanning seven countries.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Its width varies from 200 km (120 mi) to 700 km (430 mi), encompassing a series of parallel cordilleras, high plateaus, and deep intermontane valleys.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Prominent peaks such as Aconcagua at 6,961 metres (22,838 feet) in Argentina, Huascarán at 6,768 metres (22,205 feet) in Peru, and Illimani 6,438 metres (21,122 feet) in Bolivia illustrate the extreme elevations and rugged relief that define the range.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The Andes encompass a wide variety of climatic and ecological zones, ranging from humid cloud forests on the eastern slopes to the arid high plains of the Altiplano and the glaciated summits of the southern Andes.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] These sharp environmental gradients have strongly influenced human settlement and the development of major highland cities such as Bogotá, Cusco, La Paz and Quito.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] At the northern end of the Andes, the separate Sierra Nevada de Santa Marta range is often, but not always, treated as part of the Northern Andes.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The Andes are an orogenic belt of mountains along the Pacific Ring of Fire, a zone of volcanic activity that encompasses the Pacific rim of the Americas as well as the Asia-Pacific region.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The Andes are the result of tectonic plate processes extending during the Mesozoic and Tertiary eras, caused by the subduction of oceanic crust beneath the South American Plate as the Nazca Plate and South American Plate converge.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] These processes were accelerated by the effects of climate.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] As the uplift of the Andes created a rain shadow on the western fringes of Chile, ocean currents and prevailing winds carried moisture away from the Chilean coast.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] This caused some areas of the subduction zone to be sediment-starved, which in turn prevented the subducting plate from having a well lubricated surface.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] These factors increased the rate of contractional coastal uplift in the Andes.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The main cause of the rise of the Andes is the contraction of the western rim of the South American Plate due to the subduction of the Nazca Plate and the Antarctic Plate.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] To the east, the Andes range is bounded by several sedimentary basins, such as the Orinoco Basin, the Amazon Basin, the Madre de Dios Basin, and the Gran Chaco, that separate the Andes from the ancient cratons in eastern South America.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] In the south, the Andes share a long boundary with the former Patagonia Terrane.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] To the west, the Andes end at the Pacific Ocean, although the Peru–Chile Trench can be considered their ultimate western limit.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The Andean orogen has a series of bends or oroclines.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The Bolivian Orocline is a seaward-concave bending in the coast of South America and the Andes Mountains at about 18° S.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] At this point, the orientation of the Andes turns from northwest in Peru to south in Chile and Argentina.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The Andean segments north and south of the Orocline have been rotated 15° counter-clockwise to 20° clockwise respectively.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The Bolivian Orocline area overlaps with the area of the maximum width of the Altiplano Plateau, and according to Isacks (1988) the Orocline is related to crustal shortening.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The specific point at 18° S where the coastline bends is known as the Arica Elbow.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Further south lies the Maipo Orocline, a more subtle orocline between 30° S and 38°S with a seaward-concave break in the trend at 33° S.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Near the southern tip of the Andes lies the Patagonian Orocline.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The formation of the modern Andes began with the events of the Triassic, when Pangaea began the breakup that resulted in developing several rifts.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The development continued through the Jurassic Period.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] It was during the Cretaceous Period that the Andes began to take their present form, by the uplifting, faulting, and folding of sedimentary and metamorphic rocks of the ancient cratons to the east.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The rise of the Andes has not been constant, as different regions have had different degrees of tectonic stress, uplift, and erosion.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Across the 1,000-kilometer-wide (620 mi) Drake Passage lie the mountains of the Antarctic Peninsula south of the Scotia Plate, which appear to be a continuation of the Andes chain.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The far east regions of the Andes experience a series of changes resulting from the Andean orogeny.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Parts of the Sunsás Orogen in Amazonian craton disappeared from the surface of the earth, being overridden by the Andes.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The Sierras de Córdoba, where the effects of the ancient Pampean orogeny can be observed, owe their modern uplift and relief to the Andean orogeny in the Tertiary.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Further south in southern Patagonia, the onset of the Andean orogeny caused the Magallanes Basin to evolve from being an extensional back-arc basin in the Mesozoic to being a contractional foreland basin in the Cenozoic.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Many high-magnitude earthquakes have been recorded in the region, such as the 2010 Maule earthquake (M8.8), the 2015 Illapel earthquake (M8.2), and the 1960 Valdivia earthquake (M9.5), which as of 2024 was the strongest ever recorded on seismometers.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The amount, magnitude, and type of seismic activity varies greatly along the subduction zone.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] These differences are due to a wide range of factors, including friction between the plates, angle of subduction, buoyancy of the subducting plate, rate of subduction, and hydration value of the mantle material.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The highest rate of seismic activity is observed in the central portion of the boundary, between 33°S and 35°S.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] In this area, the angle of subduction is very low, meaning the subducting plate is nearly horizontal.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Studies of mantle hydration across the subduction zone have shown a correlation between increased material hydration and lower-magnitude, more frequent seismic activity.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Zones exhibiting dehydration instead are thought to have a higher potential for larger, high-magnitude earthquakes in the future.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The mountain range is also a source of shallow intraplate earthquakes within the South American Plate.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The largest such earthquake (as of 2024) struck Peru in 1947 and measured Ms 7.5.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] In the Peruvian Andes, these earthquakes display normal (1946), strike-slip (1976), and reverse (1969, 1983) mechanisms.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The Amazonian Craton is actively underthrusted beneath the sub-Andes region of Peru, producing thrust faults.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] In Colombia, Ecuador, and Peru, thrust faulting occurs along the sub-Andes due in response to contraction brought on by subduction, while in the high Andes, normal faulting occurs in response to gravitational forces.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] In the extreme south, a major transform fault separates Tierra del Fuego from the small Scotia Plate.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The Andes range has many active volcanoes distributed in four volcanic zones separated by areas of inactivity.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The Andean volcanism is a result of the subduction of the Nazca Plate and Antarctic Plate underneath the South American Plate.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The belt is subdivided into four main volcanic zones that are separated from each other by volcanic gaps.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The volcanoes of the belt are diverse in terms of activity style, products, and morphology.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Although some differences can be explained by which volcanic zone a volcano belongs to, there are significant differences inside volcanic zones and even between neighboring volcanoes.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The Andes Mountains host large ore and salt deposits, and some of their eastern fold and thrust belts act as traps for commercially exploitable amounts of hydrocarbons.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] In the forelands of the Atacama Desert, some of the largest porphyry copper mineralizations occur, making Chile and Peru the first- and second-largest exporters of copper in the world.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Porphyry copper in the western slopes of the Andes has been generated by hydrothermal fluids (mostly water) during the cooling of plutons or volcanic systems.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The porphyry mineralization further benefited from the dry climate that reduced the disturbing actions of meteoric water.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The dry climate in the central western Andes has also led to the creation of extensive saltpeter deposits that were extensively mined until the invention of synthetic nitrates.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Yet another result of the dry climate are the salars of Atacama and Uyuni, the former being the largest source of lithium and the latter the world's largest reserve of the element.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Early Mesozoic and Neogene plutonism in Bolivia's Cordillera Central created the Bolivian tin belt as well as the famous, now mostly depleted, silver deposits of Cerro Rico de Potosí.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The Andes Mountains is connected to the climate of South America, particularly through the hyper-arid conditions of the adjacent Atacama Desert.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The Atacama Bench, a prominent low-relief feature along the Pacific seaboard, serves as a key geomorphological record of the long-term interplay between Andean tectonics and Cenozoic climate.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] While the initial uplift and shortening of the Andes were driven by the subduction of the Nazca Plate beneath the South American Plate, arid climate acted as an important feedback mechanism.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Reduced erosion rates in the increasingly arid Atacama region may have effectively stopped tectonic activity in certain parts of the mountain range.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] This lack of erosion could have facilitated the eastward propagation of deformation, leading to the widening of the Andean orogen over time.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Thus, the Atacama Desert and its geological features, like the Atacama Bench, offer critical insights into the coupled evolution of the Andes Mountains and the changing regional climate.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The Andes Mountains, initially inhabited by hunter-gatherers, experienced the development of agriculture and the rise of politically centralized civilizations, which culminated in the establishment of the century-long Inca Empire.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] This all changed in the 16th century, when the Spanish conquistadors colonized the mountains in advance of the mining economy.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] In the tide of anti-imperialist nationalism, the Andes became the scene of a series of independence wars in the 19th century, when rebel forces swept through the region to overthrow Spanish colonial rule.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Since then, many former Spanish territories have become five independent Andean states.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The climate in the Andes varies greatly depending on latitude, altitude, and proximity to the sea.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Temperature, atmospheric pressure, and humidity decrease in higher elevations.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The southern section is rainy and cool, while the central section is dry.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The northern Andes are typically rainy and warm, with an average temperature of 18 °C (64 °F) in Colombia.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The climate is known to change drastically in rather short distances.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Rainforests exist just kilometers away from the snow-covered peak of Cotopaxi.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The mountains have a large effect on the temperatures of nearby areas.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The Andes of Chile and Argentina can be divided into two climatic and glaciological zones: the Dry Andes and the Wet Andes.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Since the Dry Andes extend from the latitudes of the Atacama Desert to the area of the Maule River, precipitation is more sporadic, and there are strong temperature oscillations.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The line of equilibrium may shift drastically over short periods of time, leaving a whole glacier in the ablation area or in the accumulation area.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] In the high Andes of Central Chile and Mendoza Province, rock glaciers are larger and more common than glaciers; this is due to the high exposure to solar radiation.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] In these regions, glaciers occur typically at higher altitudes than rock glaciers.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The lowest active rock glaciers occur at 900 m a.s.l. in Aconcagua.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Though precipitation increases with height, there are semiarid conditions in the nearly 7,000-metre (22,966 ft) highest mountains of the Andes.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] This dry steppe climate is considered to be typical of the subtropical position at 32–34° S.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The valley bottoms have no woods, just dwarf scrub.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The largest glaciers, for example the Plomo Glacier and the Horcones Glaciers, do not even reach 10 km (6.2 mi) in length and have only insignificant ice thickness.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] 20,000 years ago, the glaciers were over ten times longer.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] On the east side of this section of the Mendozina Andes, they flowed down to 2,060 m (6,760 ft) and on the west side to about 1,220 m (4,000 ft) above sea level.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The massifs of Aconcagua (6,961 m or 22,838 ft), Tupungato (6,550 m or 21,490 ft), and Nevado Juncal (6,110 m or 20,050 ft) are tens of kilometres away from each other and were connected by a joint ice stream network.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The Andes' dendritic glacier arms, components of valley glaciers, were up to 112.5 km (69.9 mi) long and over 1,250 m (4,100 ft) thick, and spanned a vertical distance of 5,150 m (16,900 ft).
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The climatic glacier snowline (ELA) was lowered from 4,600 m (15,100 ft) to 3,200 m (10,500 ft) at glacial times.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The Andean region cuts across several natural and floristic regions, due to its extension, from Caribbean Venezuela to cold, windy, and wet Cape Horn passing through the hyperarid Atacama Desert.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Rainforests and tropical dry forests used to encircle much of the northern Andes but are now greatly diminished, especially in the Chocó and inter-Andean valleys of Colombia.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Opposite the humid Andean slopes are the relatively dry Andean slopes in most of western Peru, Chile, and Argentina.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Along with several Interandean Valles, they are typically dominated by deciduous woodland, shrub and xeric vegetation, reaching the extreme in the slopes near the virtually lifeless Atacama Desert.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] About 30,000 species of vascular plants live in the Andes, with roughly half being endemic to the region, surpassing the diversity of any other hotspot.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The small tree *Cinchona pubescens*, a source of quinine that is used to treat malaria, is found widely in the Andes as far south as Bolivia.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Other important crops that originated from the Andes are tobacco and potatoes.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The high-altitude *Polylepis* forests and woodlands are found in the Andean areas of Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Bolivia, and Chile.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] These trees, by locals referred to as Queñua, Yagual, and other names, can be found at altitudes of 4,500 m (14,760 ft) above sea level.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] It remains unclear if the patchy distribution of these forests and woodlands is natural, or the result of clearing that began during the Incan period.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Regardless, in modern times, the clearance has accelerated, and the trees are now considered highly endangered, with some believing that as little as 10% of the original woodland remains.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The Andes are rich in fauna: With almost 1,000 species, of which roughly 2/3 are endemic to the region, the Andes are the most important region in the world for amphibians.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The diversity of animals in the Andes is high, with almost 600 species of mammals (13% endemic), more than 1,700 species of birds (about 1/3 endemic), more than 600 species of reptiles (about 45% endemic), and almost 400 species of fish (about 1/3 endemic).
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The vicuña and guanaco can be found living in the Altiplano, while the closely related domesticated llama and alpaca are widely kept by locals as pack animals and for their meat and wool.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The crepuscular (active during dawn and dusk) chinchillas, two threatened members of the rodent order, inhabit the Andes' alpine regions.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The Andean condor, the largest bird of its kind in the Western Hemisphere, occurs throughout much of the Andes but generally in very low densities.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Lake Titicaca hosts several endemics, among them the highly endangered Titicaca flightless grebe and Titicaca water frog.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] These forest-types, which includes the Yungas and parts of the Chocó, are very rich in flora and fauna, although few large mammals exist, exceptions being the threatened mountain tapir, spectacled bear, and yellow-tailed woolly monkey.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Birds of humid Andean forests include mountain toucans, quetzals, and the Andean cock-of-the-rock, while mixed-species flocks dominated by tanagers and furnariids are commonly seen—in contrast to several vocal but typically cryptic species of wrens, tapaculos, and antpittas.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] A number of species such as the royal cinclodes and white-browed tit-spinetail are associated with *Polylepis*, and consequently also threatened.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The Andes Mountains form a north–south axis of cultural influences.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] A long series of cultural development culminated in the expansion of the Inca civilization and Inca Empire in the central Andes during the 15th century.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The Incas formed this civilization through imperialistic militarism as well as careful and meticulous governmental management.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The government sponsored the construction of aqueducts and roads in addition to pre-existing installations.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Some of these constructions still exist today.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Devastated by European diseases and by civil war, the Incas were defeated in 1532 by an alliance composed of tens of thousands of allies from nations they had subjugated (e.g.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Huancas, Chachapoyas, Cañaris) and a small army of 180 Spaniards led by Francisco Pizarro.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] One of the few Inca sites the Spanish never found in their conquest was Machu Picchu, which lay hidden on a peak on the eastern edge of the Andes where they descend to the Amazon.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The main surviving languages of the Andean peoples are those of the Quechua and Aymara language families.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Woodbine Parish and Joseph Barclay Pentland surveyed a large part of the Bolivian Andes from 1826 to 1827.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] In modern times, the largest cities in the Andes are Bogotá, with a metropolitan population of over ten million, and Santiago, Medellín, Cali, and Quito.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Lima is a coastal city adjacent to the Andes and is the largest city of all Andean countries.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] It is the seat of the Andean Community of Nations.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] La Paz, Bolivia's seat of government, is the highest capital city in the world, at an elevation of approximately 3,650 m (11,975 ft).
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Parts of the La Paz conurbation, including the city of El Alto, extend up to 4,200 m (13,780 ft).
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The cities of Caracas, Valencia, and Maracay are in the Venezuelan Coastal Range, which is a debatable extension of the Andes at the northern extremity of South America.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Cities and large towns are connected with asphalt-paved roads, while smaller towns are often connected by dirt roads, which may require a four-wheel-drive vehicle.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The rough terrain has historically put the costs of building highways and railroads that cross the Andes out of reach of most neighboring countries, even with modern civil engineering practices.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] For example, the main crossover of the Andes between Argentina and Chile is still accomplished through the Paso Internacional Los Libertadores.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Only recently have the ends of some highways that came rather close to one another from the east and the west been connected.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Much of the transportation of passengers is done via aircraft.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] There is one railroad that connects Chile with Peru via the Andes, however, and there are others that make the same connection via southern Bolivia.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] There are multiple highways in Bolivia that cross the Andes.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Some of these were built during a period of war between Bolivia and Paraguay, in order to transport Bolivian troops and their supplies to the war front in the lowlands of southeastern Bolivia and western Paraguay.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] For decades, Chile claimed ownership of land on the eastern side of the Andes.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] These claims were given up in about 1870 during the War of the Pacific between Chile and the allied Bolivia and Peru, in a diplomatic deal to keep Peru out of the war.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The Chilean Army and Chilean Navy defeated the combined forces of Bolivia and Peru, and Chile took over Bolivia's only province on the Pacific Coast, some land from Peru that was returned to Peru decades later.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Bolivia has been completely landlocked ever since.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] It mostly uses seaports in eastern Argentina and Uruguay for international trade because its diplomatic relations with Chile have been suspended since 1978.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Because of the tortuous terrain in places, villages and towns in the mountains—to which travel via motorized vehicles is of little use—are still located in the high Andes of Chile, Bolivia, Peru, and Ecuador.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Locally, the relatives of the camel, the llama, and the alpaca continue to carry out important uses as pack animals, but this use has generally diminished in modern times.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Donkeys, mules, and horses are also useful.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The ancient peoples of the Andes such as the Incas have practiced irrigation techniques for over 6,000 years.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Because of the mountain slopes, terracing has been a common practice.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Terracing, however, was only extensively employed after Incan imperial expansions to fuel their expanding realm.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The potato holds a very important role as an internally consumed staple crop.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Maize was also an important crop for these people, and was used for the production of chicha, important to Andean native people.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Currently, tobacco, cotton, quinoa, and coffee are the main export crops.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Coca, despite eradication programs in some countries, remains an important crop for legal local use in a mildly stimulating herbal tea, and illegally for the production of cocaine.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] In unirrigated land, pasture is the most common type of land use.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] In the rainy season (summer), part of the rangeland is used for cropping (mainly potatoes, barley, broad beans, and wheat).
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Irrigation is helpful in advancing the sowing data of the summer crops, which guarantees an early yield in periods of food shortage.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Also, by early sowing, maize can be cultivated higher up in the mountains (up to 3,800 m (12,500 ft)).
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] In addition, it makes cropping in the dry season (winter) possible and allows the cultivation of frost-resistant vegetable crops like onion and carrot.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The Andes rose to fame for their mineral wealth during the Spanish conquest of South America.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Although Andean Amerindian peoples crafted ceremonial jewelry of gold and other metals, the mineralizations of the Andes were first mined on a large scale after the Spanish arrival.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Potosí in present-day Bolivia and Cerro de Pasco in Peru were among the principal mines of the Spanish Empire in the New World.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Río de la Plata and Argentina derive their names from the silver of Potosí.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Currently, mining in the Andes of Chile and Peru places these countries as the first and second major producers of copper in the world.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Peru also contains the 4th-largest goldmine in the world: the Yanacocha.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The Bolivian Andes principally produce tin, although historically silver mining had a huge impact on the economy of 17th-century Europe.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] In Chile in the higher portions of the Andes there are only mining districs dominated by large-scale mining, while medium and small-scale mining is more common at lower altitudes.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] For mines in the high Andes there are logistical difficulties in the use of sea water, in addition to increased probabilities of extreme weather events that may disrupt water supply.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The gold deposits of the El Indio Gold Belt tend to lie along the Argentina–Chile border and next to or below glaciers and gold mining there have thus issues relating to the bi-nationality and their environmental impacts on glaciers.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Mining in the cold conditions in the Andes pose also difficult conditions for outdoor workers such as pallaqueras and for the batteries of electrified machinery.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] There is a long history of mining in the Andes, from the Spanish silver mines in Potosí in the 16th century to the vast current porphyry copper deposits of Chuquicamata and Escondida in Chile and Toquepala in Peru.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] Other metals, including iron, gold, and tin, in addition to non-metallic resources are important.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The Andes have a vast supply of lithium; Argentina, Bolivia, and Chile have the three largest reserves in the world respectively.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] This list contains some of the major peaks in the Andes mountain range.
[src:edward-w-berry/andes-mountains] The highest peak is Aconcagua of Argentina.
[src:edward-w-berry/edward-w-berry] Berry was born February 10, 1875, in Newark, New Jersey, and finished high school in 1890 at the age of 15.
[src:edward-w-berry/edward-w-berry] Berry studied North and South American flora and published taxonomic studies with theoretical reconstructions of paleoecology and phytogeography.
[src:edward-w-berry/edward-w-berry] He started his scientific career as an amateur scientist, working with William Bullock Clark as a lab assistant in 1905.
[src:edward-w-berry/edward-w-berry] At Johns Hopkins University he held various positions including teacher, research scientist, scientific editor, provost, and dean.
[src:edward-w-berry/edward-w-berry] Berry was appointed geologist with the U.
[src:edward-w-berry/edward-w-berry] Geological Survey in 1910 along with the post of assistant state geologist for Maryland in 1917, both positions he kept until retiring in 1942.
